%I A397106 #21 Jun 21 2026 23:42:59
%S A397106 2,4,6,7,10,10,14,12,14,16,22,17,26,22,22,21,34,24,38,27,30,34,46,30,
%T A397106 34,40,34,37,58,38,62,38,46,52,46,43,74,58,54,48,82,52,86,57,54,70,94,
%U A397106 55,62,60,70,67,106,62,70,66,78,88,118,69,122,94,74,71,82,80,134
%N A397106 a(n) = n + A275314(n), for n >= 1.
%C A397106 Two-stage dissonance of the superparticular musical interval (n+1)/n.
%C A397106 The index n is the lower partial of the interval (n+1)/n, anchoring the sequence to the bass note, consistent with the two-stage perceptual model in which the lower note establishes harmonic context.
%C A397106 The superparticular (epimoric) ratio (n+1)/n is the musical interval between consecutive partials of a harmonic series: octave (2/1), fifth (3/2), fourth (4/3), major third (5/4), minor third (6/5), and so on. Since gcd(n+1, n) = 1 always, no coprimality condition is needed.
%C A397106 a(n) = T(n+1, n) in the two-stage dissonance triangle A397104, where T(n,k) = n + A275314(k) - 1.
%C A397106 The sequence is not monotone: a(7) = 14 > a(8) = 12, because A001414(8) - A001222(8) = 6 - 3 = 3, giving A275314(8) = 4, making the major second 9/8 arithmetically cheaper under this model than the septimal interval 8/7 despite 8 > 7.
%H A397106 David De Roure, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.16412">An Asymmetric Formula for Interval Consonance and its Relation to Harmonic Coincidence</a>, arXiv:2606.16412 [math.HO], 2026.
%F A397106 a(n) = n + A275314(n), for n >= 1.
%F A397106 a(n) = n + 1 + A001414(n) - A001222(n), for n >= 1.
%e A397106 a(4) = 7: the major third 5/4. Lower partial n=4, upper partial n+1=5. A001414(4) - A001222(4) = 4 - 2 = 2, giving A275314(4) = 3. a(4) = 4 + 3 = 7.
%e A397106 a(8) = 12: the major second 9/8. A001414(8) - A001222(8) = 6 - 3 = 3, giving A275314(8) = 4. a(8) = 8 + 4 = 12.
%e A397106 a(11) = 22: the undecimal neutral third 12/11. 11 is prime, so A001414(11) - A001222(11) = 11 - 1 = 10, giving A275314(11) = 11. a(11) = 11 + 11 = 22.
%t A397106 os[1]=0; os[n_Integer/;n>1]:=Total[#[[2]]*(#[[1]]-1)&/@FactorInteger[n]];
%t A397106 Table[n+1+os[n], {n,1,45}]
%o A397106 (PARI) a(n) = my(f=factor(n)); n + 1 + sum(i=1, #f~, f[i,2]*(f[i,1]-1))
%o A397106 for(n=1, 45, print1(a(n), ", "));
%Y A397106 Cf. A001222, A001414, A275314, A397104.
%K A397106 nonn,hear,new
%O A397106 1,1
%A A397106 _David De Roure_, Jun 16 2026
